##### HodlVault2 Project Rules

Every time you choose to apply a rule(s), explicitly state the rule(s) in the output. You can abbreviate the rule description to a single word or phrase.

###### Project Context

- **Purpose:** A secure vault application built with the Quasar framework and a Node.js backend, utilizing smart contracts for decentralized asset management [4].
- **High-Level Goal:** To provide a reliable interface and secure signing backend for managing blockchain-based vaults and automated withdrawal services [4].

###### Readable Code Laws (Target State)

- **Law 1: Avoid Deep Nesting.** Use inversion (guard clauses) to collapse nested structures. Return early so the reader can discard previous conditions from their mind [4].
- **Law 2: No Code Duplication.** Extract duplicated logic into shared, reusable functions or service modules. Prioritize modularization over copy-pasting [5].
- **Law 3: Meaningful Naming.** Use descriptive names that reveal intent (e.g., use auxiliary verbs like `isLoading`). Avoid shorthand that only the author understands [5].
- **Extraction Rule:** Extract complex logic into its own named function to provide a "summary" of functionality at a glance [5].
- **Cleanup Rule:** When migrating logic (e.g., from frontend to backend), immediately remove the corresponding unused legacy code to prevent ESLint `no-unused-vars` errors [6-8].

###### Codebase Structure (Monorepo)

- `apps/frontend/`: Quasar.js application [9, 10].
- `apps/backend/`: Express.js API logic and signing services [10, 11].
- `packages/shared/`: Common TypeScript interfaces, constants, and utilities used by both frontend and backend [10, 12].
- `apps/frontend/src/contract/`: CashScript smart contracts (.cash) and related JSON metadata [10, 13].
- `plans/`: Project implementation plans and blueprints [12, 14].

###### Tech Stack & Module Standards

- **Package Manager:** pnpm (version 10+) using workspaces [15, 16].
- **Frontend:** Quasar.js (Vue 3/Vite). Configuration files (e.g., `quasar.config.js`) MUST use **CommonJS (`module.exports`)** for compatibility [2, 17].
- **Backend:** Node.js (Version 20+) with Express.js and TypeScript [14, 18].
- **Shared Package:** TypeScript ESM [19, 20].
- **Alias Resolution:** When working in `apps/frontend`, ensure Vite aliases (like `#q-app/wrappers`) are correctly resolved. Always run `pnpm install` and `quasar prepare` inside the frontend directory after structural changes [8, 21, 22].

###### Coding Patterns & Conventions

- **Vue Style:** Use Vue 3 Composition API with `<script setup>` syntax [14].
- **Naming:**
  - PascalCase for Vue components [18].
  - kebab-case for all service, utility, and route files [18].
  - camelCase for functions and variables [18].
  - UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants [18].
- **Exports:** Named exports for services/utilities; Default exports for Vue components [18].

###### Backend & TypeScript Standards

- **Return Types:** Always use **explicit return types** for all TypeScript functions [18].
- **Strict Typing:** Define strict interfaces in `packages/shared/src/index.ts` for all message passing [18, 20].
- **Pure Functions:** Use the `function` keyword for pure functions to enhance readability [23].
- **Error Handling:** Use guard clauses for validation; avoid large try/catch blocks unless translating errors for the user [23].

###### Workflow & Formatting

- **Prettier Rules:** Single quotes, **no semicolons**, and 100-character print width (defined in `.prettierrc.json`) [23, 24].
- **Documentation:** Use JSDoc for services. Only include comments for complex logic; ignore the obvious [23].
- **Linter:** Cascade must automatically fix lint errors it generates using existing ESLint rules [23].

###### Git Usage

Follow these commit message prefixes (lowercase messages) [25]:

- `feat:` New features
- `fix:` Bug fixes
- `refactor:` Code refactoring
- `docs:` Documentation changes
- `chore:` Maintenance or pnpm updates
- `test:` Adding missing tests

###### Maintenance Principles

- **Keep it Concise:** Only add preferences if Cascade consistently gets a pattern wrong. Concise context reduces hallucinations [25].
- **Iterative:** Update this file constantly as you discover new problems or refine your tech stack [25].
